1 Introduction

Blood transfusion saves lives, from replacing lost blood during major surgery, a serious injury to treating various illnesses and blood disorders such as leukemia. Ensuring that theres enough blood in supply whenever needed is a serious challenge for the health professionals. There is an approximation that every 2 seconds someone in the U.S. needs a blood transfusion.

During campaigns it is usually hard to convince people to donate blood. So, we decided to use a data set found on internet to make a model to predict blood transfusions.

Our dataset is from a mobile blood donation vehicle in Taiwan. The Blood Transfusion Service Center drives to different universities and collects blood as part of a blood drive. We want to predict whether or not a donor will give blood the next time the vehicle comes to campus.

1.1 Research Question

Our goal is to predict whether a person has donated blood or not in March 2007 based on the given predictors Recency(months), Frequency(times), Monetary(c.c. blood), Time(months).

2 Dataset description

2.1 Data

The data contains 748 data points and 5 variables. This data was collected by Blood Transfusion Service Center in Hsin-Chu City in Taiwan.

Observational Unit: one blood donor from Hsin-ChU city in Taiwan.

Data description:

Variable Description
Recency(months) Number of months since the particular donors most recent donation
Frequency(times) Total number of donations that the donor has made
Monetary(c.c.blood) Total amount of blood that the donor has donated(cubic centimeters)
Time(months) Number of months since the donors first donation
Whether she/he donated blood in March 2007 This is a binary variable which represents whether the donor donated blood in March in 2007: (1 = yes/donated, 0 = no/did not donate)

4 Description and implementation of method(s)

For this project we will use logistic regression to predict the information described in our research question.

  • First, we implemented the assumption test to check the prediction for our model looks right.

  • Second, in order to see how well we predict, we used rates and probabilities, accuracy, missclassification, sensitivity, specficity, positive and negative predicted value, and confusion matrix.

  • Last, we used the crossvalidation method to estimate our test error.

4.1 Brief summary of the results

After the analysis of our logistic model using all the variables except monetary, the misclassification rate for our model was 23%, the probability of the donor donated blood in March 2007 was 0.0327, all the assumption tests passed except from DW test p-value. Due having the odd ratio greater than one for Recency and lower than one for Frequency and Time, we assume that our data did not have enough significant variables when predicting our model. According to the confusion matrix and rates and probabilities calculation, our model classification accuracy was 77% with 23% misclassification rate. Furthermore, we had 12.4% sensitivity, 97.4% specificity, 59.5% true positive rate, 78.1% true negative rate, and 23% of test error using validation set approach. Surprisingly, he test error on our test and train data is the same. The results show that our model did and will do a good job when predicting new values that the model hasnt seen.

All of the variables are statistically significant as all the p-values are less than 0.05 significant level.

After controlling for the variables, Frequency and Time, we find that the relationship between the number of months since the donors most recent donation and their odds of donated blood in March 2007 is significant (z-score = -5.692885, p = 1.249102e-08, = 0.05). Similarly, holding other variables fixed, we can find the relationship between the odds of a person donated blood in March 2007 and each variable, and we find that they are all significant as all p-values are < 0.05. However, the z-score for Recency and Time doesnt really look good, so we can find OR ratio and see if theres a relationship.

A one unit increase in the number of months since the donors most recent donation is associated with 0.906 times lower odds of the donor donated blood in March 2007. Therefore, there appears to be little evidence of a relationship between the number of months since the donors most recent donation and the donor donated blood in March 2007. Similarly, one unit increase in the number of months since the donors first donation is associated with 0.977 times lower odds of the donor donated blood in March 2007. Thus, the number of months since the donors first donation also appears to have little evidence of a relationship with the donor donated blood in March 2007.

One unit increase in the total number of donations that the donor has made is associated with 1.145 times greater odds of the donor donated blood in March 2007. Thus, there appears to be a relationship between the total number of donations that the donor has made and the donor donated blood in March 2007. As the strength of the relationship decreases with the inclusion of other covariates, more research is likely needed.

5.2 Prediction

In statistical and machine learning, our goal is often prediction. We can use the following equation to predict the probability of an event given values in our predictor space.

\[\hat{p}(X)=\frac{e^{\hat{\beta_0}+\hat{\beta_1}X}}{1+e^{\hat{\beta_0}+\hat{\beta_1}X}}\] If we have 73 months since the donors most recent donation, total number of 48 donations that has made, and 97 months since the donors first donation, we get the following.

\[\hat{p}(X)=\frac{e^{-0.44953955+-0.09858382*Recency+0.13538952*Frequency-0.02309249*Time}}{1+e^{-0.44953955+-0.09858382*Recency+0.13538952*Frequency-0.02309249*Time}}\] This donor has a 0.0327 probability of having donated blood in March 2007. If we wanted a yes/no classification prediction, we could use a threshold of 0.5. A donor with a probability below 0.5 would be predicted to not have donated blood, while a donor with a probability above 0.5 would be predicted to have donated blood in March 2007. For our predicted donor, with 0.03327 < 0.5, woud not be predicted to have donated blood in March 2007.

predicted.values<-predict(bt.model, type="response")
predicted.values[1:5]

newdata=data.frame(Recency = 73, Frequency= 48 , Time = 97) ## remember to use the exact same variable names

5.3.1 Independent Observations

#Durbin Watson test
dwtest(bt.model)
## 
##  Durbin-Watson test
## 
## data:  bt.model

Even though DW statistic is 1.73, we have a really small p-value, thus, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the residuals in this model are auto-correlated.

It predicted that 555 people did not donate blood in March 2007 and they actually did not. It predicted that 156 people donated blood but they actually did not. And also predicted that 15 people did not donated blood, but they actually did.

5.4.5 Sensitivity

Sensitivity is also called the true positive rate. Here, this is how many do we predict Donated blood on March 2007 out of all people who donated blood on March 2007. If we use M to describe our model prediction of 1 or 0 and D to describe the true class of 1 or 0, we can write the following \(sensitivity=P(true.positives | cases)=P(M=1 | D=1)=\frac{N_{true.positives}}{N_{cases}}=\frac{N_{M=1, D=1}}{N_{D=1}}\)

tpr<-df.2[df.2$predicted.Donated==1 & df.2$true.Donated==1,"count"]/sum(df.2[df.2$true.Donated==1,"count"])
tpr
## [1] 0.1235955

We can see that our true positive rate is 12.4%.

5.4.6 Specificity

Specificity is also called the true negative rate. Here, this is how many do we predict are did not donated blood on March 2007 out of all people who did not donated blood on March 2007.

\[specificity=P(true.negatives | not.cases)=P(M=0 | D=0)=\frac{N_{true.negatives}}{N_{not.cases}}=\frac{N_{M=0, D=0}}{N_{D=0}}\]

tnr<-df.2[df.2$predicted.Donated==0 & df.2$true.Donated==0,"count"]/sum(df.2[df.2$true.Donated==0,"count"])
tnr
## [1] 0.9736842

We can see that our true negative rate is 97.4%.

5.4.7 Positive Predictive Value

Of the people who are predicted to have Donated blood on March 2007, how many actually donated blood on March 2007.

\(PPV=P(true.positives | positives)=P(D=1 | M=1)=\frac{N_{true.positives}}{N_{positives}}=\frac{N_{D=1, M=1}}{N_{M=1}}\)

ppv<-df.2[df.2$predicted.Donated==1 & df.2$true.Donated==1,"count"]/sum(df.2[df.2$predicted.Donated==1,"count"])
ppv
## [1] 0.5945946

We see that 59% of the people actually donated blood out of the people who are predicted to have donated blood in March 2007.

5.4.8 Negative Predictive Value

Of the people who were predicted to have not donated blood in March 2007, how many did not actually donate blood in March 2007.

\(NPV=P(true.negatives | negatives)=P(D=0 | M=0)=\frac{N_{true.negatives}}{N_{negatives}}=\frac{N_{D=0, M=0}}{N_{M=0}}\)

npv<-df.2[df.2$predicted.Donated==0 & df.2$true.Donated==0,"count"]/sum(df.2[df.2$predicted.Donated==0,"count"])
npv
## [1] 0.7805907

We see that 78% of the people did not actually donate blood in March 2007 out of the people who were predicted to have not donated blood in March 2007.

One important additional note. Here, we are evaluating how well the model did on the TRAINING dataset. We would expect the classification to not be as good for a TEST data set. Indeed, classification performance on a test dataset estimates the generalizable error, which is what we are most interested in. Therefore, we will use cross-validation to estimate test error.

6 Discussion/conclusion

In conclusion, we found out that our model had 77% of accuracy which indicates our model did a good job. We also noticed that based on our test error (23%) our model will perform good on future data that the model hasnt seen. Our p-value for Durbin Watson test was of 0.0001301 which shows that we reject the Null and conclude that the residuals of this model are auto-correlated. A way to improve our model can be going back to the data collection and add some more significant variables that can help us predict if a person will donate blood in the future or not, such as if there is monetary compensation, blood type, age, health condition and others. Some of the advantages of using cross-validation method is that it is easy to implement, it can estimate the generalization performance of the model, and can reduce over fitting. One of the disadvantages of cross validation is that its computationally expensive.
